        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation activity relevance acceptance criteria — MRL 5",
        "description": "Validation experiments must use the same pump geometry, the same blood analogue fluid properties, and operating conditions spanning the full COU envelope; any deviation from COU conditions must be bounded by a documented similarity argument with quantified extrapolation uncertainty."
      },
      "rationale": "Validation experiments use the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry and a glycerol-saline blood analogue at matched viscosity and density. However, the experiments were conducted at hematocrit 35% whereas the COU specifies 40–45% hematocrit for the target patient population. A similarity argument is provided but the extrapolation uncertainty for the 5–10% HCT difference is not quantified, leaving a marginal gap from level 5 to achieved level 4."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cou2/numerical-solver-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Iterative solver residuals (L2 norm) are monitored to machine-precision convergence (10⁻⁸) at every time step for all transport equations. Solver error is therefore bounded well below discretization error and cannot materially affect the hemolysis QoI. This factor is scoped out at MRL 5 on the basis that iterative convergence is demonstrably not the limiting error source; the dominant uncertainty is discretization error, which is separately assessed."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cou2/use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "All simulation runs are executed through a validated, locked simulation workflow managed by the SQA-controlled pipeline; no manual mesh generation or solver configuration steps are exposed to the analyst. User-introduced error is structurally prevented by the workflow architecture. This factor is scoped out because the use-error pathway is eliminated by design, not merely mitigated, and residual risk is captured under the Software quality assurance factor."
    },
    {
